The Telegraph - Calcutta : International
 Monday, May 03, 2004  Fine Print				 				 				 																Music of love London, May 2 (AFP): John Lennons son and the daughter of Mick Jagger, singer of rival sixties British band the Rolling Stones are getting their ya-yas out, though not in the musical sense, Jaggers former wife said. 																																	They are so in love, oozed Jerry Hall, mother of 20-year-old model Elizabeth, in the Daily Telegraph newspaper, revealing the seven-week romance with Sean, 28, the son of the late Beatle and his wife Yoko Ono. 																																	Jerry Hall, 47, who was Jaggers partner for 25 years, also announced plans to release her first single in December. She will talk-sing with a backing band to include her ex-husbands former bassist Bill Wyman, Who guitarist Pete Townshend and Bob Geldof. 																													 																Brave talkBerlin (Reuters): Troy director Wolfgang Petersen said he is an adventurer at heart and dreams of fighting great battles  and he would draw a sword for his wife if necessary. I have a longing for adventure but Im probably just too comfortable for true adventure, he told Germanys Bild am Sonntag newspaper. Troy is about the legendary 10-year conflict between Greeks and Trojans over the abduction of Helen, wife of Greek hero, Menelaus. The film stars Brad Pitt as the Greek hero Achilles.																													 																Prince pardon																																	 Riyadh (Reuters): A Saudi prince has been saved from the executioners sword by a last-minute pardon by the father of the teenager he murdered. Prince Fahd bin Nayef, a minor Saudi prince aged 19, stood blindfolded and ready for death on Saturday. But, according to the daily Asharq al-Awsat, when he said Free me, for the sake of God, and may God free you from hell, the father of murdered youth Munthir al-Qadi decided to pardon him.
